The agent should think in terms of business tasks. The application should think in terms of implementation details.

TextExpander is an absolute MUST for developers. It's not an efficinet use of time to type out concole.log('thing', thing') over and over again (for example). Instead I use ccopy my varibale name and type ;cl.

Docbot is given a small number of high-level business tools rather than low-level GitHub operations. This keeps the agent focused on reasoning about documentation while the application retains responsibility for deterministic tasks such as repository operations, authentication, retries and validation.

Its like the aAI is the human focussed on the high level thinking tasks and the app is the AI doing the repetitive work. 

The agent is responsible for judgement, not execution. It decides what documentation should change and why. The application is responsible for deterministic operations such as communicating with GitHub, validating responses, creating branches and opening pull requests.

On a deeper level, we are as humans recreating our own existence with software engineering. we have basic functions to do mundane tasks, think CRON jobs, schedulers, data retreival. Then we have the next alyer which actually makes decisions, if this do this, else do this. The next level above that can manipulate and compare data (does the date of this meeting coincide with the date of the next meeting? if so we need to tell our human about it). And now with the event horizon of AI we are adding yet another layer - reasoning. 
To me these are directly mappable onto the human experisnece. basic functions - breathing, heartbeat. NExt layer which makes decisions - is the body hydrated? no? make human feel thirsty. energy running low? make human sleepy. Then we have the pattern matching subconscious/semi-conscious layer. and finally our reasonaing selves.
